segments.text: there, Dean Stangle, and we won that contest in Fort Worth.
So were you also a member of the junior livestock fishing team?
The junior team then, what, did that stay in Texas?
Well, yeah.
Well, we judged at Fort Worth and at Oklahoma City.
Oklahoma City.
And the senior livestock?
Well, the senior team judged the International in Chicago.
But did you have to go to Fort Worth and Oklahoma City?
You just went to Chicago, huh?
Yeah.
Had to fire for that team, too, you know.
So if you made the junior team, you weren't automatically on the senior team.
That's right.
Were there ever anybody other than the animal husbandry majors on the team?
Not in those days, because, well, they
They didn't take enough courses in law taught judging to where they made it anyway.
But I think now, I think that's changed now, I'm not sure.
Mostly though, it's having 100 students.
Because they take a lot of courses in, they don't call it judging anymore, I think they call it evaluation or something like that.
This morning I took a little bit of time and read the history of your class that's in the 22.
Daniel Longhorn.
Longhorn, yes.
And there was something in there that I didn't fully understand.

This would have been during your junior year, and this mission was made of some kind of an embarrassing incident that was, you know, possibly would reflect adversely upon both the school and the student body.
And the
Whoever wrote the class history said something to the effect that the class of 22 did right and everything went on OK.
I suspect that that might have had something to do with hazing, but I don't.
Well, it might have had something to do with the junior banquet.
I think they cut out the junior banquet about in that time.
This would have been the 2021 year, I think.
The junior bankers got pretty rough sometimes.
It was the, they'd always tried to, they didn't know who the tool smasher was gonna be and they wouldn't announce it.
But the other boys would try to find out and if they, and they'd get who they thought it was gonna be and take him way out here in the woods somewhere and keep him to learn at the bank.
Now you say they, who was they?
Well, all the other students.
The other three classes?
Yeah.
What was the purpose of the junior banquet?
Just a social function?
Yes.
But this was something attended only by members of the junior class or did they bring guests also?
Yeah.
We had, we were talking about entertainment in those days, I guess our dances was our biggest social entertainment.
We'd have our ROT, the Ross volunteers always had a dance and
The junior class would have dance, sophomore, freshman.
They'd have final ball and all that kind of stuff.
And they were quite popular because we had to import our girls, you see.
Either from other schools.
Where did they stay then?
There were a lot of houses on the campus in the profs and these profs would keep them.
Because at that point there was no hotel in town, no motel.
No, they stayed with the profs.
Earlier, in a sense, before we turned on the machine, you were telling me something about an incident involving Senator Parr and one of his sons.
Could you start over?
Well, Senator Parr's son, George Parr, was going to school here.
And he went over and told me that there was hazing going on over here.
And Senator Parr had a committee.
formed over there, and they come over here to inspect and look into it.
And they told the commandant to have those boys that George told them was being hazed to go down to the hospital and be inspected.
So when they come, they could have them up for the committee.
And of course, Dr. Zell, they told him when it's coming and all.
So Dr. Zell got a student body together and told them about it.
Told them to put on their
their good manners and treat them like gentlemen.
And of course the kids knew what that meant.
That meant to really put on the red carpet.
And of course everybody traveled by train those days when the committee came down to the depot to get off while they was met there by the band.
And the band played the march while they marched up to the YMCA where they had this meeting.
And when
Archie Parr started acquitting these boys after he put them on their oath.
He couldn't get much out of them.
He asked the boy, he said, were you hazed?
He said, no.
He said, now son, you're on the oath.
It'll be hard on you if you don't tell the truth.
He says, I ask you again, were you hazed?
He said, no, sir, I wasn't hazed.
Well, he said, what are those black and blue stripes on the back of your
rump for it if you hadn't been hazed that you were expected down there at the hospital.
He said my roommate and I were exchanging licks last night and they never made a thing out of that but George had to leave school.
Do you remember what year that was?
I believe 1920.
One other student of an earlier
had mentioned something about some hazing in which some students were dropped from school, and it was involved the son of a state senator.
I was wondering if it might have been.
Well, it could have been.
Well, I don't think it was this one, because that was Hans Brody, class of 17, who was involved in that incident, and that was probably another state senator's son.
Well, you know, there were a lot of boys come here,
in those days, and they didn't stay.
They didn't like it.
You know, a school like this at that time, I guess same way now, but I liked it myself.
But a lot of boys didn't like it, and so they left.
You've probably heard of, out of the class, if 100 boys came here, freshmen, only about half of them graduated seniors, or maybe less.
And they all, the rest of them, either changed schools or dropped out of college, won.
I don't know where they went.
But, you know, some boys like some schools, some don't.
I think the way you were raised before you got here had something to do with it.
Yeah, I'm sure it did.
You said you were accustomed to hazing.
I was accustomed.
I had three brothers older than I was, I think.
They wasn't too kind to me.
And another thing, I had to milk a cow every night for supper and every morning for breakfast when I was at home.
Came down here and ate supper without even milking a cow, ate breakfast without milking a cow.
I thought I was really going to town.
You really had to make that.
Yeah.
OK. Oh.
One or two incidents that happened while you were here, and I just wanted to see if you had anything to add to them.
Well, one happened before you came.
That was the famous branding of the University of Texas mascot.
13 to nothing, yeah.
13 to nothing.
I didn't remember anything about that.
Well, somewhere we had picked up some information.
Matter of fact, we have an invitation.

that was sent out apparently by some people in Austin to a banquet in Austin and it's January 22nd and the best we can figure out this was 1920 and that was inviting people to this banquet in Austin and it was a barbecue and that's supposed to have been barbecued Bevo and we had some other indication that Bevo was slaughtered and the hide was tanned and
and split, and A&M got half, and Austin got, UT Austin got half.
Have you ever had any?
No, that's all news to me.
That's all news to you.
Well, there was a newspaper clipping, and maybe the invitation was a fake.
I mean, maybe it was a joke.
Yeah, it could be.
But we've been told that the Beagle never made a public appearance again after he was branded.
Uh-huh.
So, uh.
Well, I know the boys, you know, they tried to get the mascot.
I know they went out and got the owl one time.
But I think Dr. Dell didn't take that back.
Yeah, see, we talked a little bit about what you've done after you graduated, and we want to talk some more about that.
You indicated the first year you came back and
and worked on a master's, and then you worked for the railroad for a while, and then you came back to A&M in 25.
Stayed until I retired in 65.
But we want to talk a little bit more about what you did while you were here.
We don't want to just skip over it and say that.
Well, until they combined the Extension Service, Experimentation, and College in one unit, I was with Experimentation 100%.
And so I was with the research from 1925 until they combined it about 1946.
In 1947 I came over here and I was half teaching and half research.
And when I was doing research, we got interested in problems that
that our farmers and ranchers and other citizens were interested in, like a cottonseed meal for pigs.
Before I got started in that, we had a
This is a book on pork production.
When I studied in school, and here's how I'd have to answer that question to get a hundred on it when I was in school.
I'd get zero on it today.
Cutting seed meal is poisonous to swine.
That's the way you learned it in school.
Well, that last sentence there.
It is poisonous to swine if you talk about it.
Mm-hmm.
Doesn't it say no way it's been found to feed it to swine?
Well, see, as now prepared cottonseed meal is poisonous to swine, all the various proposed ways for safely feeding this meal have failed under careful and continued tests.
Yeah.
Pigs thrive at first on the meal, but usually in from four to six weeks, some die.
Not all is a rule, but so many that all possible profits from the use of this feed are lost.
Yeah.
Now, read this right here, then.
cotton seed meal may be fed safely.
As a result of much research and many practical experiences, it has been shown how cotton seed meal may be used in swine rations safely.

Hale of the Texas Station, in a comprehensive series of experiments from 1924 to 1928, demonstrated that it could be fed safely to all classes of hogs when certain restrictions as to amount and conditions were observed.
Well, that
That did us a lot of good.
I was proud of A&M, you know, to come out of A&M College.
I put A&M above me.
It's interesting how things...
when you're in school, what you, some things you're told that is true at that time, but may not be true tomorrow.
Now you take this, I don't know where you've heard of this vitamin A work we did on pigs or not.
Just briefly, that I knew you did some.
But before we did that, the literature, all this basic science of literature says that a birth defect
is a result of hereditary factor.
In other words, if she was born with some birth defect, it's due to genetics.
Well, uh, we came, we got to working on the vitamin A and, uh,
And our work was reviewed by a lot of people.
Here's one by Dr. Hogan of Missouri.
He tells something about that there.
What we showed was that the birth defects may be caused by environmental factors as well as by hereditary factors.
And the environmental is anything that's not hereditary.
And this thing here is put out by the University of Copenhagen at Denmark.
And they have verified our work.
About 30 years later, you'll see this published in 1966.
And we gave our first talk.
Our first talk was over here in Atlantic City at the American meeting of ophthalmology.
And they, when they put out this issue, they put our talk was the first one in the journal.
Relation of vitamin A to antifamilies from pigs.
That's small eyes.
But what it really showed that it produced
not only blindness, but a lot of other birth defects.
And now that, here's a picture of a normal pig's eye.
That's a normal pig's eye.
And there's a pair of abnormal pig's eyes.
And here's a hair lip, cleft palate, cyst,
And the exterior light grows at the base of the ear.
And we just, that just showed up everywhere.
And then the signs started taking this up everywhere.
And they've been like in Denmark here, trying to verify that, you know, or just prove it.
And here is the yearbook of pediatrics, 1934.
And they put a picture of our pigs in there and told about it.
And then...
quoted our work about 10 different years.
Here she is, Paladin.
She sent this to me.
And there's a different page that she's got referred to our work here on this.
So I think if we did anything called as any good, that cut and seam meal work and this work was
not only accepted here in this state, but nationally, internationally.
Like, here's what she says right here on page 90, and then all these other pages here.
But she came up with the same, when she gave her studies, started her program, she got the same thing that we got.
Our first letter was born in 1932.
Also, the Texas Medical Association invited us to give a talk up there at Fort Worth in 1937.
And they put it on the radio.
But there's a few things we did like that that I was awfully interested in research.
And of course, I was interested in teaching, too.
But I was in research for over 20 years before we did it.
Let me back up and ask a question about the cottonseed business.
Why were you trying to figure out how you could feed cottonseed meal to pigs?
Was it you were trying to find a use for a commodity?
Oh yeah, you see that was a Texas cotton.
The cotton was a big crop for Texas and 1500 pounds of picked cotton
give you a bale of cotton of 500 pounds and 1,000 pounds of seed.
And that seed is processed in the oil and cottonseed meal.
And then it's fed to livestock.
And people keep asking me, why can't we feed cottonseed meal to pigs?
And I went through the literature like that book there.
It says you can't feed it.
And that's what I was taught.
So I went to the library and started checking up on the...
data that they used to come to that conclusion.
And I found data where they're feeding as much as 30% cottonseed meal to pigs, and then came to that conclusion.
Well, so I just asked myself a question, was I could say that about salt.
If I fed 30% salt in the ration, that salt's poisonous to pigs and you can't feed it.
So I set up my own project, experiment, and started out with a lot with no cottonseed meal in it,
and then the other feed that took the place was tankage, a protein supplement called tankage.
And then I took out a little tankage and put in 3% cotton seed meal, then another lot, 6% cotton seed meal, 9% cotton seed meal, 12% cotton seed meal, and 15% cotton seed meal and no tankage.
Well, the reason I stopped at 15, that balanced the ration as far as protein is concerned.
And so as long as I didn't go above 9% cotton seed meal,
I couldn't tell those pigs from the growth rate and efficiency of feed utilization from the ones that didn't have any cottonseed meal.
And that's why we wrote it up that way.
And then people started getting on that to try to verify that.
And they came up with the same results we did in Nebraska and other places.
So that you had an abundance of cottonseed meal.
Yeah.
And you needed to find a use for it.
Well, farmers asked me, I want to feed some cottonseed me.
Why can't I feed cottonseed me to the pigs?
And since we was out here in charge of the swine laboratory, well, they thought we ought to do some work on that.
And the Texas Cottonseed Products Association asked us to do a little work on that.
And we came up with that bulletin, and then now every
every bulletin that's published from now on out when it comes to cottonseed meal, or if you're near Marsden's Feeding Feeder or anything, quotes our work on that.
Well, I take it that cottonseed meal itself has a... it's a protein.
Yes.
And so, therefore, it should be beneficial, but what you then have to do is find out what proportion of it... Well, cottonseed meal is as...
Cotton seed has a toxic substance in it for pigs called gossypo.
And the reason they call it gossypo, the OL signifies it's a phenol or carbolic acid compound.
And the gossy comes from gossypium, which is a botanical name for cotton.
So they call it gossypo.
And gossypo will kill pigs, no doubt about that.
So we later then set up a test to find out how much gossypo a pig could tolerate.
And it's .01%, that small amount.
And if you get over that, you're going to kill the pig.
But when you don't go over 9% of your ration as a cottonseed meal, you'll never have any trouble with gospel.
So the ration then was composed of like 9 or less percent cottonseed meal, and then what, grain?
Grain and tankage.
or anything else you want to put in there.
If you can't have something, it's a meat scrap or soybean meal or something to add up the protein to the level it should be.
So what, the level of the protein should be what, 30%?
Well, depending on the age of your pig.
Now, a pig at weaning time needs about 18% crude protein in the ration.
But a 200-pound pig, it needs only about 12% to 14% protein.
Brood sows in a supplement period need about 15% crude protein.
And we fed this cottonseed meal to brood sows and all stages of pigs, fed to boars, growing and fighting pigs, and brood sows in the gestation period and in the lactation period.
So was cottonseed meal then was a more economical
It was cheaper, yes.
It was cheaper than tankage or something else that would provide protein.
When you added two together, well then you had a better protein supplement anyway.
Uh-huh.
And then you say your other primary development was the vitamin A studies for pigs.
How did you come to work on that project?
The literature is full of information on the need of animals for vitamins, even humans and everybody.
And so the direct experiment station here asked the different divisions to write up a project for their dairy cattle and beef cattle and pigs and poultry and all on the vitamin studies.
And we picked vitamin A.

for pigs because all of our farm grains are deficient in vitamin A except yellow corn and we don't, Texas is not over abundant in yellow corn, we have grain sorghum and grain sorghum doesn't have any vitamin A.
So we thought that we should determine the amount of vitamin A a pig needs and the sources of this vitamin A and the effect of vitamin A on the gestation period of the sow and lactation period
all this.

And then as we went along, we uh, we wanted to, we picked gilts, or females, for our study because we wanted to know what effect it had on the estrous period, or the heat period of the gilt, and the number of pigs she had, and how she gave milk for them, and what the pigs had, the growth effect, the growth of the pigs, all that.
Well, we had one
here to get out and couldn't get up.
We had to give her some cod liver oil.

Of course, we knew enough about the vitamin A from the literature that one of the symptoms of vitamin A deficiency in pigs is that they can't walk straight because the nerve controls locomotion is degenerated.
And they walked behind legs, they'd cross them this way, and they'd act like they were almost drunk.
And so when she got that way, well, they gave her some cod liver oil, and she got all right.
And then a little later when she was down, before she got this far down, we bred her.
And then she got down 30 days later, couldn't get up, so we gave her cod liver oil.
And then when she had litter of pigs, well, they were all blind.

Well, we knew how we'd been treating this sow, so we decided then maybe we'd better set up the test to deplete the sow's vitamin A storage in her body, which there's a lot of it in her liver and other organs.
And then when she's depleted of her vitamin A storage breeder and keep her on this depletion for 30 days longer, that's when the facial eyes and the other facial cells develop in the embryo.
And so we'd give her a lot of cow liver oil and it would be too late to repair this.
And we kept producing.
Every time we did that, we'd get blind pigs.
So we came to this conclusion.
We had to prove it genetically.
We know that vitamin A is necessary for you to normalize the function.
If you don't take vitamin A, you're going to have night blindness and things like that.
So the question actually comes to you,
If vitamin A is necessary for the normal eye to function, is it necessary for the development of the eye in the embryo?
And that was the question.
And then you set up that premise, then you start your feeding and your experiments to prove yourself wrong or right.
And so...
We published all this thing in the Journal of Heredity.
And this organization here then got a hold of that and read that.
It was also published in the American Society of Animal Production.
And so they asked us to prepare a paper for this meeting here.
And I sure did feel humble and not prepared to do this because I was just 35 years old and I knew I'd be up there with people from Harvard and Yale and all that place.
So I went over to see my director and talked to him about it because he was very
They were very proud that we'd get an invitation to a thing like that.
He says, Fred, you just stay with the data you've got.
And if they ask you questions that your data doesn't cover, just tell them that your data doesn't cover that question.
And say write it in, what you got on your data, and say they'll never get you in a hole anywhere.
And it worked just exactly like that.
